t" id=3D"content"><article class=3D"content"><div id=3D"site-search-results=
-main"></div><h1>How to Install Telnet on Mac [2025]</h1><p>Need to use Tel=
net on your Mac? Only to find out at the most
inopportune time that Telnet is no longer on MacOS? Well, take
solace in the fact that you=E2=80=99re not alone. Telnet has
been removed from modern versions of the system software starting from
MacOS Mojave and newer. These instructions will work for MacOS Mojave and
newer, including Sonoma and Sequoia (These are the steps that I have person=
ally
used to get Telnet back).</p><h2 id=3D"installing-telnet-on-macos-with-home=
brew">Installing Telnet on MacOS with Homebrew</h2><p>The first way (which =
is the easiest) is to use Homebrew to install telnet.</p><h4 id=3D"step-1-i=
nstall-homebrew-if-not-already-installed">Step 1: Install Homebrew (if not =
already installed)</h4><p>If you don=E2=80=99t already have Homebrew on you=
r machine, either follow step 1
below or navigate over to <a href=3D"https://brew.sh/">the website</a> and =
follow
their installation instructions. Once installed move on to step 2.</p><div =
class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, 242);=
 background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" class=
=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span style=
=3D"display:flex"><span>$ curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebre=
w/install/master/install.sh
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Open and inspect th=
e install.sh script to see and make sure what it does.
And then run it.</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; p=
osition: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-l=
ang=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ ./install.sh
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><h4 id=3D"step-2-insta=
ll-telnet">Step 2: Install Telnet</h4><p>After installing Homebrew, install=
 Telnet</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb=
(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position: =
relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"ba=
sh"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ brew install telnet
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>That=E2=80=99s it, =
get back to whatever you needed telnet for.</p><h2 id=3D"installing-telnet-=
on-macos-by-building-telnet-from-source">Installing Telnet on MacOS by Buil=
ding Telnet from Source</h2><p>This was the method I used. There are some p=
rerequisite steps though,
if you don=E2=80=99t already have them you=E2=80=99ll need to install the M=
acOS command line tools (step 1 below). If you already have them installed =
skip to <a href=3D"https://hakk.dev/blog/posts/getting-telnet-on-macos-cata=
lina/#step-2-getting-the-telnet-source">step 2</a>.</p><h4 id=3D"step-1-ins=
talling-the-command-line-tools">Step 1: Installing the command line tools</=
h4><p>Open a terminal and enter the following line, you=E2=80=99ll then be =
shown a
pop up prompt.</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"col=
or: rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; pos=
ition: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lan=
g=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ xcode-select --install
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Click install when =
the prompt pops up.</p><figure><picture><source srcset=3D"/imgs/xcode-macos=
-command-line-tools.webp" alt=3D"" title=3D"command line tools install prom=
pt" type=3D"image/webp"><img src=3D"https://hakk.dev/imgs/xcode-macos-comma=
nd-line-tools.png" alt=3D"command line tools install prompt" title=3D"comma=
nd line tools install prompt" loading=3D"lazy"></picture><figcaption>comman=
d line tools install prompt</figcaption></figure><p>After that you=E2=80=99=
ll be shown a license which you=E2=80=99ll have to agree to
in order to install.</p><figure><picture><source srcset=3D"/imgs/command-li=
ne-tools-license-agreement.webp" alt=3D"" title=3D"command line tools licen=
se agreement" type=3D"image/webp"><img src=3D"https://hakk.dev/imgs/command=
-line-tools-license-agreement.png" alt=3D"command line tools license agreem=
ent" title=3D"command line tools license agreement" loading=3D"lazy"></pict=
ure><figcaption>command line tools license agreement</figcaption></figure><=
p>After that you=E2=80=99ll see the download progress and the install will =
happen
after that. Unfortunately I forget to get screen shots of the following
message boxes.</p><figure><picture><source srcset=3D"/imgs/command-line-too=
ls-download.webp" alt=3D"" title=3D"command line tools download progress" t=
ype=3D"image/webp"><img src=3D"https://hakk.dev/imgs/command-line-tools-dow=
nload.png" alt=3D"command line tools download progress" title=3D"command li=
ne tools download progress" loading=3D"lazy"></picture><figcaption>command =
line tools download progress</figcaption></figure><h4 id=3D"step-2-getting-=
the-telnet-source">Step 2: Getting the Telnet source</h4><p>For this step y=
ou=E2=80=99ll be getting the <a href=3D"https://www.gnu.org/software/inetut=
ils/">GNU network utilities</a>
navigate to the <a href=3D"http://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/inetutils/">download page=
</a>
and find the latest source. At the time I=E2=80=99m writing this it=E2=80=
=99s 2.5:</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: r=
gb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position=
: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"=
bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ curl -O https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/=
inetutils/inetutils-2.5.tar.xz
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Next grab the signa=
ture file and keyring file to verify:</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabi=
ndex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40=
, 34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"=
language-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ curl=
 -O https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/inetutils/inetutils-2.5.tar.xz.sig
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><div class=3D"highligh=
t"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color=
: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><co=
de class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex">=
<span>$ curl -O https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/gnu-keyring.gpg
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Finally verify:</p>=
<div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, =
242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" =
class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span s=
tyle=3D"display:flex"><span>$ gpg --verify --keyring ./gnu-keyring.gpg inet=
utils-2.5.tar.xz.sig inetutils-2.5.tar.xz
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>This should produce=
 some output that says " Good signature from=E2=80=A6" within it. If that=
=E2=80=99s not the case, your download isn=E2=80=99t good and I would not p=
roceed any further.</p><h4 id=3D"step-3-extract-the-source">Step 3: Extract=
 the source</h4><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color=
: rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; posit=
ion: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=
=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ tar -xvf inetutils-2.5.tar.x=
z
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><h4 id=3D"step-4-confi=
gure-and-build">Step 4: Configure and build</h4><p>Now that the source is e=
xtracted change into the directory:</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabind=
ex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, =
34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"la=
nguage-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ cd ine=
tutils-2.5.tar.xz
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Run the configure c=
ommand:</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb=
(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position: =
relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"ba=
sh"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ ./configure
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Run the make comman=
d to build:</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color:=
 rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; positi=
on: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=
=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>$ make
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><h4 id=3D"step-5-insta=
ll-telnet">Step 5: Install Telnet</h4><p>And then install:</p><div class=3D=
"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, 242); backgro=
und-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" class=3D"has-=
copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span style=3D"displ=
ay:flex"><span>$ sudo make install
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><h2 id=3D"telnet-alter=
natives---command-line-tricks">Telnet Alternatives - Command Line Tricks</h=
2><p>Depending on your use case of Telnet you might be able to find an alte=
rnative tool to use.</p><p>Using it for network troubleshooting, to test if=
 a port on a remote server is open:</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabind=
ex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, =
34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"la=
nguage-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>telnet e=
xample.com <span style=3D"color:#ae81ff">80</span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>Trying 93.184.216.34...
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>Connected to example.com.
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>Escape character is <span =
style=3D"color:#e6db74">'^]'</span>.
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>^<span style=3D"color:#ae8=
1ff">\^</span><span style=3D"color:#f92672">]</span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>telnet&gt; q
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>Connection closed.
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Instead it would be=
 possible to use netcat (nc). It=E2=80=99s a versatile and powerful command=
-line utility that can be used for reading from and writing to network conn=
ections using TCP or UDP. Netcat is often referred to as the =E2=80=9CSwiss=
 Army knife=E2=80=9D of networking tools due to it=E2=80=99s ability to alm=
ost everything you can imagine in regards to TCP, UDP, or UNIX sockets.</p>=
<p>Here=E2=80=99s an example of using it to test a remote server port:</p><=
div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, 2=
42); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" c=
lass=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span st=
yle=3D"display:flex"><span>nc -zv example.com <span style=3D"color:#ae81ff"=
>80</span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>Connection to example.com =
port <span style=3D"color:#ae81ff">80</span> <span style=3D"color:#f92672">=
[</span>tcp/hbci<span style=3D"color:#f92672">]</span> succeeded!
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Another option is c=
url, it is a powerful command line tool that can be used for a number of ca=
ses. It also supports a large number of protocols which includes telnet.</p=
><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248,=
 242); background-color: rgb(39, 40, 34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;"=
 class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D"language-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span =
style=3D"display:flex"><span>curl -vvv telnet://example.com:80
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>*   Trying 93.184.216.34:8=
0...
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>* Connected to example.com=
 <span style=3D"color:#f92672">(</span>93.184.216.34<span style=3D"color:#f=
92672">)</span> port <span style=3D"color:#ae81ff">80</span> <span style=3D=
"color:#f92672">(</span><span style=3D"color:#75715e">#0)</span>
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Curl can also be us=
ed as a telnet client with the following command, you=E2=80=99ll need to pr=
ovide the username and password. In my case the output isn=E2=80=99t partic=
ularly nice but it will do in a pinch.</p><div class=3D"highlight"><pre tab=
index=3D"0" style=3D"color: rgb(248, 248, 242); background-color: rgb(39, 4=
0, 34); tab-size: 4; position: relative;" class=3D"has-copy"><code class=3D=
"language-bash" data-lang=3D"bash"><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>curl =
--telnet-option TTYPE<span style=3D"color:#f92672">=3D</span>vt100 telnet:/=
/example.com:23
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>user
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>461349fdd345 login: user
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>Password:=20
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>Welcome to Alpine!
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>The Alpine Wiki contains a=
 large amount of how-to guides and general
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>information about administ=
rating Alpine systems.
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>See &lt;http://wiki.alpine=
linux.org/&gt;.
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>You can setup the system w=
ith the command: setup-alpine
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>You may change this messag=
e by editing /etc/motd.
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>whoami
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>461349fdd345:~$=20
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>^<span style=3D"color:#f92=
672">[[</span>33;17R
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>461349fdd345:~$ whoami
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>user
</span></span><span style=3D"display:flex"><span>^<span style=3D"color:#f92=
672">[[</span>35;17R
</span></span></code><button class=3D"copy-btn" type=3D"button" aria-label=
=3D"Copy code to clipboard">Copy</button></pre></div><p>Hopefully this guid=
e will help get you up and running no matter if one of the alternative opti=
ons helped or if you choose to install or build. You should be up and runni=
ng within 10 minutes even if you build from source!</p></article><aside cla=
